":"1430–1462","1430–Male":"1430–Deceased","1435–Female":"1435–Deceased","1455–1501":"1455–1501","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1404–Female":"1404–Deceased","1 January 1455":"1 January 1455","1404":"1404","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1380":"1380","1549":"1549","1428":"1428","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southeast), Dutch, and Czech: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’ (see   Hermann  ). In England this name was introduced by the Normans.","Irish: variant of   Hargadon  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): perhaps a nickname for someone with a copious or noticeable head of hair (see   Haar  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hargadon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","Irish (Sligo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hArgadáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Argadán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>argad</i> ‘silver’. In Galway the traditional form <i>O'Hargadan</i> has tended to be replaced by <i>Hardeman</i>, and elsewhere in Ireland by   Harman   and   Harmon  ."]},{"name":"Herman","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Dutch, Flemish, Hungarian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Slovenian, and Croatian: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Harman   5.","Americanized form of German   Hermann  , a cognate of 1 above.","English: perhaps a shortened form of <b>Herniman</b>, a topographic name for a ‘dweller (in a) nook or corner of land’, from Middle English <i>herne</i>, <i>hirne</i>, <i>hurne</i> + <i>man</i>. See also   Hearn  ."]},{"name":"Hermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":119,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Harman was born in 1430, in England, his father, Sir Walter Harman, was 50 and his mother, Anna Sidney Lady Sutton Coldfield Warwickshire, was 26. He married Elizabeth Elham. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1430–":"1430–Surnud","1428–1477":"1428–1477","1430–1462":"1430–1462","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1455–1501":"1455–1501","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1 January 1455":"1. jaanuar 1455","1404":"1404","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1380":"1380","1549":"1549","1428":"1428","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–":"1430–Kuollut","1428–1477":"1428–1477","1430–1462":"1430–1462","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","1455–1501":"1455–1501","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1 January 1455":"1. tammikuuta 1455","1404":"1404","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1380":"1380","1549":"1549","1428":"1428","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, England":"Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–":"1430–Décédé","1428–1477":"1428–1477","1430–1462":"1430–1462","1430–Male":"1430–Décédé","1435–Female":"1435–Décédée","1455–1501":"1455–1501","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1404–Female":"1404–Décédée","1 January 1455":"1 janvier 1455","1404":"1404","1501":"1501","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1380":"1380","1549":"1549","1428":"1428","Sutton Coldfield, Warwickshire